  <span class="eyebrow">Troubleshooting &amp; repairs</span>
  <h1>Electrical troubleshooting that focuses on root cause, not guesswork</h1>
  <p>
    Good repair work starts with diagnosis. Breaker trips, flickering lights,
    dead outlets, partial power loss, and inspection concerns often point to a
    larger issue than the visible symptom. The repair process should identify
    what failed, explain why it happened, and leave you with corrective work
    that improves reliability instead of creating a repeat call.
  </p>
  <ul class="checklist">
    <li>
      Structured troubleshooting for recurring and hard-to-pinpoint issues
    </li>
    <li>
      Clear explanation of likely cause, corrective options, and priorities
    </li>
    <li>
      Strong fit for homes, remodels, and light commercial spaces with active
      use
    </li>
  </ul>
  <div class="cta-row">
  <a
    class="btn btn-primary"
    href="/booking"
    data-cta="booking"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Request Scheduling</a
  ><a
    class="btn btn-ghost"
    href="tel:+16163347159"
    data-cta="call"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Call / Text</a
  >
</div>

</section>

<section class="container section-stack section-stack--tight">
  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <h2>Common issues we diagnose</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Repeated breaker trips and overloaded circuits</li>
        <li>
          Flickering lights, intermittent power loss, and unstable connections
        </li>
        <li>Hot, dead, or unreliable outlets and switches</li>
        <li>Problems exposed by inspections, remodels, or equipment changes</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h2>What a good repair call should deliver</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>Root-cause findings instead of surface-level assumptions</li>
        <li>
          Code-aware corrective work where unsafe or outdated conditions are
          found
        </li>
        <li>
          Recommendations for preventing recurrence when additional upgrades
          make sense
        </li>
        <li>
          Clear communication before the scope grows beyond the original symptom
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <h2>Why troubleshooting quality matters</h2>
  <p>
    The cheapest repair is not always the one that costs the least over time.
    Replacing the visible failure without understanding the cause can leave the
    underlying circuit, connection, load issue, or equipment condition
    unchanged. A better service call isolates the reason, fixes the right thing,
    and tells you when related work should be handled now versus later.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <div class="process-grid">
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>1</strong>
      <h3>Symptom review</h3>
      <p>
        Identify what is happening, when it happens, and what else changed
        around the same time.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>2</strong>
      <h3>Targeted diagnosis</h3>
      <p>
        Test and isolate likely failure points instead of replacing parts by
        guesswork.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>3</strong>
      <h3>Corrective work</h3>
      <p>
        Complete the repair, correction, or replacement with safety and future
        reliability in mind.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>4</strong>
      <h3>Next-step guidance</h3>
      <p>
        Explain what was found and whether other improvements should be planned
        to prevent the issue returning.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>
  <details>
    <summary>Can you fix issues flagged during an inspection or sale?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes. Inspection findings often need verification, prioritization, and
      focused corrective work rather than blanket replacement.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What if the issue only happens occasionally?</summary>
    <p>
      Intermittent issues can still be diagnosed, especially when the symptom
      pattern and affected loads are described clearly at the start.
    </p>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>
      Do repair calls sometimes turn into upgrade recommendations?
    </summary>
    <p>
      Yes. Some service calls reveal larger capacity, panel, or code-correction
      issues that are worth addressing once the immediate problem is understood.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

